"This naturally leads me to the defence of the fa- mous anachronism, in making /neas and Dido con- temporaries ; for it is certain, that the hero lived almost two hundred years before the building of Carthage. One, who imitates Boccalini %, says that Virgil was accused before Apollo for this error. The god soon found that he was not able to defend his favourite by reason ; for the case was clear : he therefore gave this middle sentence, that any thing might be allowed to his son Virgil, on the account of hig other merits ; that, being a monarch, he had a dispensing power, and pardoned him. But that this special act of grace might never be drawn into"